/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

STEP #2, LEAVE HOUSE:

Depends on the calc.
Calc 1 is ez mode just read up on the general power rule, chain rule, and the trig derivatives and you'll be mostly set. The rest will fall in line naturally after that.
Calc 2, I don't remember terribly but if you are having issues with the approximation stuff just look for simular problems are focus on the method on how they solve it. If it's the stuff where you have to try certain methods to do stuff, you will generally find that some methods work with some general equations. If not, rinse wash and repeat with another method.
But I would usually try to use substitution first.
Calc 3 is just calc 2 on drugs and you will eventually learn series. Series are basically how to make a general form of the results of an equation. Try to abuse -1^n and (n+1)! as much as you can. The approximation stuff is pretty specific and you just have to remember the methods.
I have very terrible memory, so I can't remember much of what was taught to me. I just happen to grasp it in short term fairly well. Plus, my tests/exams are take-home question that the profs think are fun to torment us with.
